Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @lemon{1/2}.

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} and pop them onto a piece of #foil{} with a drizzle
of oil, the @honey{1%tbsp} and a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Fold the foil, sealing on all sides to create a parcel, then pop it onto a #baking tray{}.

Pour the @water for the stock{750%ml} into a medium #saucepan{} on high heat. Stir in
the @vegetable stock paste{20%g}.

When the oven is hot, roast the tomato parcel on the bottom shelf until softened,
~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a large saucepan on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{1%pack}, garlic and
@sun-dried tomato paste{25%g} and cook for ~{1%minute}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the @risotto rice{175%g}, then stir and cook until the edges of the rice are
translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}. Squeeze in the lemon juice and cook until evaporated,
~{1%minute}.

Pour in a third of the stock and stir to combine.

Bring to the boil and simmer until absorbed, then repeat with the remaining stock,
a third at a time. Stir occasionally.

The cooking time should take ~{20-25%minutes} and your risotto is done when your
rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the
middle.

Once the risotto is cooked, stir in the roasted tomatoes (discarding the juices),
@grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g} and @butter{30%g} until combined. Taste and
season with salt and pepper if needed.

Crumble in half the @goat's cheese{75%g} and stir through. Remove from the heat.
Add a splash of water to loosen if needed.

Share the tomato risotto between your #bowls{} and crumble over the remaining
goat's cheese.

Top with a handful of @wild rocket{20%g}.

Enjoy!